<New PAsource="" >A man with a history of sex attacks stretching back more than 20 years was jailed for life yesterday for the murder </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >of </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >a </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >21 year old prostitute. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >David Smith, 43, from Hampton, west London, picked up Amanda Walker </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >in </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Paddington, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >west </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >London, in April after attending a party in Ilford, Essex.
</Verbatim>

<New PAsource="" >He drove her to </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >a Surrey beauty spot </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >where he raped and murdered her. </New>
<New PAsource="" >He then mutilated her body, the Old Bailey was told. </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >He </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >dumped her blood stained clothing on a footpath a mile from his home.
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >The recorder of London, Judge Michael Hyam told Smith: "Anyone who has heard what you did to that unfortunate young woman must have been horrified and revolted by what you did to her after you killed her."
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >Smith had denied murdering Miss Walker, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >who had just moved to London from Leeds.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >The court heard Smith committed his first sex assault </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >when he was </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >18. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >He </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >was jailed for </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >four years </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >in 1976 for </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >raping a </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >woman </Rewrite>
<New PAsource="" >at knifepoint at her home in west London </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >in front of her two children.
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >Miss Walker's body was found in a shallow grave near the Royal Horticultural Society gardens at Wisley nearly six weeks after she disappeared.
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >Her body, covered with leaves and branches, was found by an </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >RHS </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >employee. 
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >"He noticed a pungent smell and thought it might be a dead deer but saw it was a decomposing body," William Boyce, prosecuting, told the court.
</Verbatim>


